	<article class="article ">
		<header class="block-content block-content-l1 block-content-center">
						<div class="block-content-header">
				<h6 class="b-content-section heading-square"><a href="/sections/essays-memoirs-true-stories">Essays, Memoirs, and True Stories</a></h6>
				<h1 class="block-content-title">Virus</h1>

				
				<ul class="block-content-meta list-inline-border tiny"><li>
							By <a class="meta-article-contributors" href="/contributors/alison-luterman">Alison Luterman</a></li><li><a href="/issues/262">October 1997</a></li></ul>

			</div>

								</header>

				<div class="article-body link-text-wrap">
																		<p class="text-right"><em>for J. S., in memoriam, 1959&ndash;1996</em></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="dropcap">We hold our support-group meetings in a room with Oriental carpets and deep green easy chairs. I arrive a few minutes early to set out chips, cookies, a foil tray full of fried-chicken dinners, and a liter bottle of Coke. Food is a big draw. One by one, they drift in.</p>

<p>Chris leans on his cane, looking skeletal yet elegant in his homemade African cape. He can take an old piece of cloth, twist it over his shoulder, and create an outfit with character, nuance. In his day (&ldquo;when I had a body&rdquo; is how he refers to it), Chris was a porn star and a great drag queen. Sometimes, when he feels up to it, he comes to group in his drag persona, Zsa Zsa: red lipstick, ringletted wig, skintight dress, and high heels. I love Zsa Zsa &mdash; she&rsquo;s delicate and wispy, like a monarch butterfly with only one day to live. But today Chris is an old African king, leaning heavily on his walking stick, with a cloth-of-gold skullcap atop his shaven head. He takes his seat on the red couch, his stick resting between his knees, his deeply sunken eyes closed. Lately, he has often slept through group meetings. I don&rsquo;t say anything. He&rsquo;s close to the end now. My co-worker Imelda got him into a hospice with a nurse on call twenty-four hours a day and a private chef. For hospice you have to have a note from your doctor saying you&rsquo;re not expected to live six months.</p>

<p>Imelda shows up carrying a stack of napkins and the sign-in sheet. He often remembers what I forget. Imelda is a beautiful, fey African American man-girl, fluid, tactful, and funny. One of the best things about this job is getting a warm hug from Imelda each day. It is unthinkable that the heart of this twenty-eight-year-old co-worker, dancer, and friend &mdash; the heart I feel thumping against my own when we embrace &mdash; is pumping HIV-infected blood through his body.</p>

<p>Next comes Carlo, a big, glossy Jamaican. Once, he was a basketball player, then a successful businessman, till his addiction to prostitutes and gambling brought him down. When he tested positive, he had to leave his country; his family disowned him. Now he pushes a shopping cart all night long, collecting bottles and cans to recycle. &ldquo;It won&rsquo;t be this virus that kills me,&rdquo; he often says, in his thick Caribbean accent. &ldquo;It&rsquo;ll be the loneliness.&rdquo; He shuffles to his favorite chair on arthritic knees. He can&rsquo;t collect SSI because he doesn&rsquo;t have citizenship papers. I keep pushing him to see an immigration lawyer, but he&rsquo;s scared of being deported. I&rsquo;ve come to respect Carlo as a stubborn man of few words with no taste for drama. He pulls the plastic wrap off his chicken dinner and begins to eat methodically.</p>

<p>Then a surprise: Mack appears in the doorway. Mack&rsquo;s a Vietnam vet, a straight white guy, his belly swollen by liver disease, who was referred here from the VA hospital, where he&rsquo;d been receiving treatment for alcoholism. The alcohol was competing with the virus to see which could kill him faster. The last &mdash; and only &mdash; time Mack came to group, he sat next to J. J., a brilliant, bitter, queeny black guy who wears too much mascara and likes to antagonize people who can&rsquo;t accept his sexuality. When J. J. had his turn to speak, he described in excruciating detail his last sexual encounter, with a rock-hard, abusive guy &mdash; his favorite kind &mdash; who fucked him all night and wouldn&rsquo;t use a condom. J. J.&rsquo;s been out on a speed binge for the past few weeks. I expect him back any week now, skinnier, with more of those awful craters speed freaks get on their faces from picking at imaginary blemishes. He&rsquo;ll be repentant, defensive, full of excuses and bullshit. I&rsquo;m glad he&rsquo;s not here today; he was too much for Mack. At the end of that meeting, Mack told everyone he was sorry, but he didn&rsquo;t feel comfortable with the gay men in the room.</p>

<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s just not for me,&rdquo; he said firmly in answer to my protests that we were all just people dealing with the virus and the problems that come with it.</p>

<p>I am the real minority in this room: I&rsquo;ve tested negative. At least they don&rsquo;t have to worry that I&rsquo;ll get sick.</p>

<p>We&rsquo;ve got five people now, enough to start. Plus, J. J. could drop in any minute, and I want Mack to have a chance to speak before that happens. We begin with him.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I came here to make amends,&rdquo; Mack says in the straightforward way of a man with no time to waste. &ldquo;After the last group, I got to thinking I&rsquo;d been a real asshole. I&rsquo;ve been turning it over and over in my head and .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. you know, it&rsquo;s you gay people who are out there marching and telling the government it&rsquo;s got to do something about this damn virus before we all die. You&rsquo;re the ones chaining yourselves to the gates, saying we need more trials, and speaking out on TV. And in a way you&rsquo;re doing it for me. When you think about it, I&rsquo;m alive because of you. I owe you an apology, and that&rsquo;s what I came here to do.&rdquo;</p>

<p>He looks around uncertainly. Now I&rsquo;m sorry J. J. isn&rsquo;t here to hear this straight white man apologize to him. It would have been a first.</p>

<p>Several of us start to respond to Mack, but it is Chris who prevails. He speaks with the spiritual authority of an elder, which in this group he is, not because he&rsquo;s the oldest, but because he&rsquo;s the nearest to death. &ldquo;I wasn&rsquo;t here the other week when you came in,&rdquo; he says, &ldquo;so I didn&rsquo;t hear whatever it was you had to say about gay people.&rdquo; He shifts painfully on the couch, dark shadows underneath his jutting cheekbones. &ldquo;But I think it takes a real man to come back to a group and say he&rsquo;s sorry. And if you want someone to accept your apology, I&rsquo;ll do it.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Mack nods stiffly. It&rsquo;s done.</p>

<p>It&rsquo;s moments like this one when I think this job is worth it.</p>

<p>After group I go upstairs to the office, and waiting for me is Timmy, here for his results. I remember him from two weeks ago when he came in to take his test, a funny little speed freak, twitchy but kind of polite, as if straining to act normal.</p>

<p>I look at his sheet to prepare myself: negative. That&rsquo;s good. He&rsquo;s been sharing needles, though, and having unprotected sex with men &mdash; taking all the dangerous risks.</p>

<p>I usher him in and close the door behind us. He looks nervous, though he&rsquo;s trying not to show it. I don&rsquo;t mind that he&rsquo;s afraid &mdash; maybe fear will get him to clean up his act.</p>

<p>I ask him if he wants to hear his results.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah,&rdquo; he says.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Negative.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;You sure?&rdquo; he asks.</p>

<p>&ldquo;You seem surprised.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s just that .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. I know I been doing all that stuff, and my buddy Mark&rsquo;s got it. And we was ripping and running together all those years. I just sort of figured it&rsquo;d be my turn one of these days.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s like Russian roulette. Mark&rsquo;s luck ran out. Yours hasn&rsquo;t &mdash; yet. Did we talk about the window period?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah, you told me, and they went over it a million times in prison. They show movies and shit.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;So you know you&rsquo;ve got to use condoms and not share needles and &mdash;&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah, I know it; everybody knows it, but that don&rsquo;t make no difference when you&rsquo;re on the street and you want to fix and someone else is holding and you gotta fuck him or suck him or use his needle to get some of his dope. If you want it, you just do it, you know?&rdquo;</p>

<p>I&rsquo;ve heard this many times before; there&rsquo;s not a lot to say in response. &ldquo;I guess it comes down to what you want most.&rdquo;</p>

<p>He grins ruefully. &ldquo;Right.&rdquo; He barely comes up to my shoulder. His body is compact and muscular, like a miniature weight lifter: upturned nose, gray-blue eyes, short spiky hair. There&rsquo;s something childlike and innocent about Timmy, even though he&rsquo;s thirty; it&rsquo;s as if he&rsquo;s never had a chance to grow up. He has tattoos up and down his arms and all over his chest &mdash; or at least the bits that show through his torn T-shirt &mdash; lacy blue spider webs and anchors and whales and angels and devils. He&rsquo;s been in jail off and on ever since he was twelve &mdash; first detention centers and juvenile halls, then county jails and state penitentiaries. He&rsquo;s homeless, lives mostly in the park because he can&rsquo;t stand to have walls around him after being locked up for so many years.</p>

<p>Even though he has his results, Timmy seems to want to hang around and talk.</p>

<p>&ldquo;So, how&rsquo;s it going?&rdquo; I ask.</p>

<p>He shrugs. &ldquo;OK, I guess. I&rsquo;m off the street.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;That&rsquo;s great.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah, I&rsquo;m staying with my buddy Mark.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;You don&rsquo;t seem that happy about it.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Well, it&rsquo;s just that he&rsquo;s dying and shit.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;That sounds hard.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;It is. Last stages, man. It&rsquo;s fucking horrible. They got him all hooked up with tubes and wearing fucking diapers. He made me promise he would die at home; he don&rsquo;t want to be dumped off at no fucking hospital. But now it&rsquo;s like, I don&rsquo;t know if I can do it. It&rsquo;s just me and him in this tiny little apartment, and Mark is like .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. half the time he&rsquo;s totally out of it.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Does the AIDS Foundation know? Is he on SSI? Does he get Open Hand?&rdquo; I do the social-services dance, trying to pass the buck. It&rsquo;s late and I want to go home. I&rsquo;m just supposed to counsel people about their tests and facilitate the group. Someone else take care of this, please.</p>

<p>Timmy gives me the look my questions deserve. &ldquo;Yeah, we got that stuff. The Open Hand people come around. We got food. And he&rsquo;s supposed to have this social worker from SSI, but <em>she</em> don&rsquo;t do shit. Mark says he don&rsquo;t want that anyway. He just wants to stay high till he dies.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I feel totally helpless, but I&rsquo;ve gotten used to feeling this way. The reality is there&rsquo;s only so much I can do, only so much I have the energy to do, only so much I know how to do. I can&rsquo;t go to Timmy&rsquo;s apartment and drag his roommate to the hospital &mdash; if Timmy&rsquo;s story is even true, which I have no way of knowing. But this rationalization sits uneasily with me. Someone should check it out. Someone should take care of it.</p>

<p>&ldquo;How can I help <em>you</em>, Timmy?&rdquo; I ask. &ldquo;I mean, Mark&rsquo;s not here, and you are.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Can I come by sometimes, just to talk, even though I don&rsquo;t have it?&rdquo;</p>

<p>I think of what Carlo says: the virus is loneliness. This guy is so high-risk I could justify the time to my supervisor, call it prevention. &ldquo;Yeah, of course. I&rsquo;d love to see you.&rdquo;</p>

<p>He looks relieved, like a little boy who&rsquo;s just wriggled through a hole in a fence.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="dropcap">This is not the life I thought I would get. That life included marriage, children, safety. I didn&rsquo;t know I would be talking with drug addicts about the needle-exchange program the way I used to talk to friends about which classes to take. I didn&rsquo;t know I would be dating Troy.</p>

