<p>&ldquo;See? Tail end,&rdquo; she says with satisfaction.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Mmm .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. what <em>do</em> lesbians do in bed together, anyway?&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;We cuddle and hold hands,&rdquo; she murmurs.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Sounds good to me,&rdquo; I say.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="dropcap">Another night, a week later. I&rsquo;m staring into space as Troy tells me about her day.</p>

<p>&ldquo;So, where are you?&rdquo; Troy asks abruptly.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Huh?&rdquo;</p>

<p>I&rsquo;ve been obsessing about Chris. Out of nowhere, he&rsquo;s decided to move back to North Carolina, to the abusive fundamentalist family that rejected him for being queer in the first place.</p>

<p>I don&rsquo;t want to lay all of this on Troy. People who aren&rsquo;t insane enough to do the work I do shouldn&rsquo;t have to hear about it, and I don&rsquo;t want to talk about my job on my time off. This is supposed to be my safe place &mdash; except life doesn&rsquo;t work that way. I sigh and try to explain.</p>

<p>&ldquo;He said he got tired of watching the other guys in hospice die all around him. He&rsquo;d make friends with someone, and then <em>boom</em>, the guy would die on him. Finally, he stopped wanting to get close to new people as they came in.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;That makes sense.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;Yeah, I can understand that, too. But to go back east .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. His family won&rsquo;t even tell neighbors about the virus; they&rsquo;re saying he has cancer. And to leave us, to leave this city where he marched every year in the Gay Pride Parade wearing a G-string and a feather headdress &mdash; I can&rsquo;t accept it.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;It doesn&rsquo;t sound like you have a choice,&rdquo; Troy says.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t. That&rsquo;s the kicker.&rdquo;</p>

