<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s too much for anyone to handle all by themselves, Timmy. Right now, I&rsquo;m thinking &mdash;&rdquo; I take a deep breath &mdash; &ldquo;you should check into the psych ward, because maybe you&rsquo;re a danger to yourself. I know it sounds scary, but they can watch you there. You won&rsquo;t be alone; there&rsquo;ll be people taking care of you.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s a locked ward, right?&rdquo;</p>

<p>It wouldn&rsquo;t be right to lie. &ldquo;Yeah, it&rsquo;s locked. You&rsquo;ll have to stay there three days.&rdquo;</p>

<p>He starts to moan and shake his head. &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t do it, man. I just can&rsquo;t do it.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;The thing is, Timmy, if something were to happen to you, it would be on my head, see? Just like Mark&rsquo;s death is on yours. If you died, I&rsquo;d feel responsible.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I don&rsquo;t tell him the truth: that I&rsquo;d <em>be</em> responsible, and therefore I have to commit him whether he agrees to it or not. I want him to go of his own accord; I don&rsquo;t want him hauled off in a straitjacket.</p>

<p>He lifts his head. &ldquo;Oh, man, I wouldn&rsquo;t want you to feel like I feel now. I wouldn&rsquo;t want a dog to feel like I&rsquo;m feeling now.&rdquo;</p>

<p>He lets me call Psych Emergency Services, and I wait out on the street with him, holding his hand until the van shows up. Ten or fifteen years ago, I would have wrestled harder with the voice inside me that said, &ldquo;This man doesn&rsquo;t need a mental hospital; he just needs someone to take him in, sit with him, and listen to his story.&rdquo; That was before I had boundaries.</p>

<p>All the way home on the rocking train I think about Timmy. In the middle of his distress, he did something for someone else: he agreed to go to the hospital so I wouldn&rsquo;t have to suffer what he was going through. That&rsquo;s a lot of compassion for a little junkie who grew up in jail. That would be a stretch for anyone.</p>

<p>Will he be OK? Did I drop the ball last month when he first told me his story?</p>

<p>In a daze, I go to my car and drive home. The virus is loneliness.</p>
